metadata.name: Henoheno Samurai #2811
metadata.description:
This work was inspired by Otsu-e(大津絵), a Japanese painting in the Edo period. Otsu-e were inexpensive paintings made as souvenirs. Although mass-produced using paper stencils, the artisans painted by hand, resulting in variations in the quality of their work. Connoisseurs found them interesting and collected them as works of art. Otsu-e showed a new value of beauty in Japanese art, different from Ukiyo-e (浮世絵) which are prints, and from fine art paintings which are one-of-a-kind artworks.

This work is made of canvas2D Bezier curves. Not just a combination of parts, but also a random displacement of the Bezier curve points to lose the shape. This is intended to create fun with the Otsu-e-like effect.


Features:
This profile is made up of 8 parts (brows, eyes, nose, mouth, ear, contour, hair, and body). Each part has 100 basic types. 
There are 7 skin colors and 12 kimono colors. Each RGB value of the colors is randomly added within a range of ±10. In addition, there are 70 kimono patterns. 
The distortion rate due to displacement of Bezier curve points is 0.0~50.0. 


BTW The title "Henoheno" is taken from the Japanese character picture "Henohenomoheji" known since the Edo period.

metadata.name: .L◿◸ps #2
metadata.description:
"Loop" is a fundamental property of a program that means to repeat a particular part of the program. In shape, it is the curved shape made when something long and thin, such as a piece of string, bends until one part of it nearly touches or crosses another part of it. By adding randomness to loop of repetition, I expressed it as an assembly of topological loops.


- 41*2 Color Palette
- 4 Shape Types
- 5 bands


Generative art by @ConatusLab
Built in Javascript with p5.js.


Press 's(S)' to save a png.
Press 'f(F)' to full screen.
Press '1-4' to change the resolution. The size of the dots in the background changes to give a different impression.('5-8' are similar functions, but they are experimental introductions, so the load is heavy)

metadata.name: Microreactors/A Box of Chocolates #77
metadata.description:
Objects drifting in a cell generate beautiful and complex patterns. They look like "Concentration fluctuations caused by thermal convection in microreactors". It also evokes Forrest Gump's famous line "Life is like a box of chocolates".

There is a phase difference between adjacent cells, generating similar but different patterns.

Each of them can be seen as a parallel world of life.

In addition, the observer can interfere with the pattern by clicking and dragging the mouse.

metadata.name: prismatic drift #66
metadata.description:
prismatic prift is an exploration of video synthesis that delves into the dynamic potential of a single pixel column. utilizing hydra video synthesizer, this work initiates with the leftmost pixel column, which is then subjected to a series of displacements, rotations, and modulations. these actions are executed through short, repeating gestures and signals that meticulously orchestrate the emergence of complex, chaotic yet controlled micro-patterns and motions.

videosynth weekly studies 00
realtime on hydra videosynthesizer

press s to save a screen capture

made in Buenos Aires, Argentina. 02/2024

metadata.name: RULES (for Elementary Cellular Automata) #197
metadata.description:
An important element of generative art is emergence. The most famous algorithm for this is probably Cellular Automata (CA).

However, numerous generative artists have created works using CA, which has lost its visual freshness and is like chewing gum that has lost its taste.

Although it is such a classic algorithm, adding my own little ideas to it and finding a new "flavor" is the reason why I code.

Here, the subject is 1D Elementary Cellular Automata, the simplest of all cellular automata. 1D Elementary Cellular Automata has 256 different rules, which change the shapes produced. This work aims to create more complex shapes by randomly selecting some of those rules and placing multiple of them on the screen.

The on/off of the CA cell is often likened to the behavior of living creatures.As of 2022, in the country where I live, prices are rising, wages are not increasing, and COVID-19 has not yet ended. I created this work with the image of people at the mercy of these various rules.

---

Screen click: Change rules
S key: Save png
L key: Show/hide grid

metadata.name: Monocell #30
metadata.description:
Monocells have 7 features which approximately describe their configuration and behavior. Starting from a basic primitive shape, a monocell develops in several stages through application of growth rules. Higher stages give a more complex structure, with stage 3 being the highest observed for a monocell. Very rarely, stage zero appears as well, which is the primitive itself with no growth rules applied. Magnitude defines the size of the monocell by indicating the number of digits for the total number of nodes. While most monocells are symmetric, some evolve irregular configuration, which is indicated by their order. Finally, connection and degeneration features describe additional rules for adding and removing links between the nodes.

Press o_o for recording an animation clip (available only in fullscreen / live mode). Press >< for recentering. Coded in Javascript and GLSL using Three.js and D3 frameworks.

metadata.name: falling water #26
metadata.description:
# controls:
click the UI at the bottom or use hotkeys
[M]ODE: switch mode 1 ~ 4 (or use number keys)
[F]ADE: toggle fade on/off
[S]PARKLE: toggle sparkle on/off
[C]LEAR: clear all

and
[E]XPORT: export as png
space: toggle play/pause


# variables:
6 Spakle Colors: Blue / Purple / Pink / Green / White / Gold
3 Wave Levels: Small(30%) / Medium(50%) / Large(20%)
Inversed: Yes(20%) / No(80%)
Full Height: Yes(10%) / No(90%)
Timing: Sync(60%) / Async(40%)
Stroke: Hard(80%) / Soft 1(10%) / Soft 2(10%)

there are 4 modes to “fall”. you can combine the modes with fade & sparkle to get different effects.
press “E” to save as png. if you want to print it out as a postcard or whatever, append `&ratio=2` to the URL to run the @2x version. (maximum 5)
(sorry i can't make them totally the same thing, but close)

i hope you do enjoy it.

made with p5js
